  "prompt": "Should I write \"Dear Professors\" or \"Dear Prof. A, Prof. B and Prof. C\", while writing an email to 3 professors?",
  "response": "When writing an email to multiple professors, the choice between \"Dear Professors\" and \"Dear Prof. A, Prof. B and Prof. C\" depends on the context and how formal or specific you want to be.\n\n1. **\"Dear Professors\"**  \n   - Use this if you want a more general and concise salutation.  \n   - Suitable when the email is addressed to them as a group and the content applies to all equally.  \n   - Less specific, but still polite and professional.\n\n2. **\"Dear Prof. A, Prof. B and Prof. C\"**  \n   - Use this if you want to be more formal and personalized.  \n   - Ideal if the email is specifically for these individuals and you want to acknowledge each of them by name.  \n   - Slightly more formal and shows attention to detail.\n\n**Considerations:**  \n- If the professors are from different departments or fields, listing their names might be more appropriate.  \n- If you\u2019re unsure, \"Dear Professors\" is a safe and professional choice.  \n\nExample:  \n*General context:* **Dear Professors,**  \n*Formal/personalized context:* **Dear Prof. Smith, Prof. Johnson, and Prof. Lee,**  \n\nChoose the option that aligns best with the tone and purpose of your email!",
